2 who data

We will work on the who dataset (use the help page to get more details about the data). First, let’s transform the data based on what we did in class to obtain the who2 data.

names(who) <- str_replace(names(who), "newrel", "new_rel")
who2 <- who %>%
  pivot_longer(5:60, names_to="codes", values_to="case" ) %>%
  select(-iso2, -iso3) %>%
  separate(codes, c("new", "type", "sexage"), sep = "_") %>%
  select(-new) %>%
  separate(sexage, into = c("sex", "age"), sep = 1,convert=TRUE)

3 More and more on flights dataset

  1. Explain what the following code does.
airports %>%
  semi_join(flights, c("faa" = "dest")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat))+
  geom_point()

  1. Here’s an easy way to draw a map of the United States. The borders() function adds the borders for the states. (You need to install and load the maps package.)
airports %>%
  semi_join(flights, c("faa" = "dest")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
  borders("state") +
  geom_point() +
  coord_quickmap()
